*Step 1: Import Libraries
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

*Step 2: Load CSV File
# Replace 'sales.csv' with your actual file path
df = pd.read_csv("sales.csv")
# Quick look at the data
print(df.head())
print(df.info())

*Step 3: Basic Aggregations with groupby() + sum()
Let’s assume your CSV has columns like: Date, Product, Region, Sales.
# Total sales by product
sales_by_product = df.groupby("Product")["Sales"].sum().reset_index()
print(sales_by_product)

# Total sales by region
sales_by_region = df.groupby("Region")["Sales"].sum().reset_index()
print(sales_by_region)

# Monthly sales trend (if Date column exists)
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"])
monthly_sales = df.groupby(df["Date"].dt.to_period("M"))["Sales"].sum().reset_index()
monthly_sales["Date"] = monthly_sales["Date"].astype(str)
print(monthly_sales)

*Step 4: Visualizations with plot()
python
# Sales by product (bar chart)
sales_by_product.plot(x="Product", y="Sales", kind="bar", legend=False)
plt.title("Total Sales by Product")
plt.ylabel("Sales")
plt.show()
# Sales by region (pie chart)
sales_by_region.set_index("Region").plot(kind="pie", y="Sales", autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.title("Sales Distribution by Region")
plt.ylabel("")
plt.show()
# Monthly sales trend (line chart)
monthly_sales.plot(x="Date", y="Sales", kind="line", marker="o")
plt.title("Monthly Sales Trend")
plt.ylabel("Sales")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

***Outcome***
You’ve loaded a CSV with pandas.
Used groupby() + sum() to aggregate sales.
Built charts (bar, pie, line) to visualize insights.
Delivered results in a Jupyter Notebook format.

***This gives you basic data insights:***
Which products sell the most
Which regions contribute the most
How sales trend over time
